analysis: Das Exemplar I 10140 stammt aus der Bibliothek des Leipziger Sudhoff-Instituts für die Geschichte der Medizin. Diese Sammlung entstand durch Einkäufe auf dem Antiquariatsmarkt. Das Exemplar ist in einem Pergamentbroschur des 17. Jahrhunderts gebunden. Auf dem vorderen Schmutzblatt befindet sich ein sehr  verblasster Besitzeintrag: E. Wohlmill ? Wohlmuth ? 1864. Ferner gibt es auf diesem Blatt einige bibliographische Angaben (Erwähnungen von Gilbert in anderen Werken). Das Buch selbst hat vereinzelte handschriftliche Randbemerkungen wohl des 18. Jhdts, meist Verweise auf andere Autoren. Eingelegt ist ein handschriftliches Blatt (wohl 19. Jhdt) mit einen längeren Zitat aus Cardanus De Subtilitate.

analysis:
ho controllato l'esemplare di Gilbert Tractatus, sive Physiologia nova de magnete, magneticisque corporibus & magno magnete tellure, sex libris comprehensus, a Guilielmo Gilberto … e non ho trovato al suo interno annotazioni scritte a mano. Le uniche note manoscritte sono relative a vecchie segnature (annotazioni a lapis nella carta di guardia anteriore) e al suo possessore, Vincenzo Viviani, discepolo di Galileo Galilei ("W" nella carta di guardia anteriore e nota di possesso autografa sul frontespizio).
Colgo l'occasione per informarla che stiamo procedendo alla realizzazione di un progetto su Vincenzo Viviani che prevede anche la digitalizzazione e la messa in rete di un centinaio di volumi appartenuti all'allievo preferito di Galileo (fra i quali il volume di suo interesse) che si trovano presso la Biblioteca Biomedica
provenance: Vincenzo Viviani

analysis:
Der Band von 1628 enthält im Vorwort und im "LIBER SEXTUS - DE TELLURIS GLOBOMAGNOMAGNETE" zahlreiche Unterstreichungen in roter Farbe. Einige dieser Unterstreichungen sind so hoch angesetzt, dass man auch eine Durchstreichung vermuten könnte.
Die Bände unterscheiden sich in der Montage der Zeichnungen und Diagramme. 1628 wurde am Ende ein Anhang eingerichtet, der die Bilder enthält. 1633 wurden diese Blätter im Inhalt mit eingebunden.
Auf der Seite 160 wurde nur die Seitenzahl mit Bleistift korrigiert. Das mag der selbe Bibliothekar gewesen sein wie beim 1630er - Band ?!?? Ist schwer zu erkennen, da diese Stelle etwas überbelichtet ist.
Die Seite 215 ist ohne handschriftliche Anmerkung. Diese liegt nur der Paginierung folgend ordnungshalber dabei.
Zum Beispiel der Anhanggestaltung. Die Graphiken sind auf Photopapier erstellt. Stammen also sicherlich nicht aus 1628, oder was meinen Sie?

Es handelt sich nur um wenige Unterstreichungen, Korrekturen (?) u.ä. An einem Blattrand kann man Schrift erahnen, die aber nicht von der Rückseite durchgeschlagen ist, sondern vielleicht abgedruckt von einem daraufliegendem Blatt mit frischer Tinte. Lesbar ist es wohl nicht.
provenance: Og-3 Vorbesitz: Hanniel, Ignaz *-1608*

analysis: I checked the copy requested by you and unfortunately, it does not contain manuscript marginal notes or underlinings. It bears only one actually, but it is in pencil, thus must be from a later period (I am sending you the picture of it in attachment). There is also one initial partially coloured in by hand with black ink (vide picture). However, the book bears historic ownership marks - one was probably cut out from the last leaf (vide picture) and another one, on the recto of B3 ("Pro Coll[egio] Crac[oviensi] SS. Petri et Pauli liber hic comparatus post incendium 1719" ; vide picture) proves that this book belonged to the Jesuits' library in Cracow (you can find the short note on this library in CERL Thesaurus, unfortunately it is in Polish only: https://data.cerl.org/thesaurus/cnc00009418 ).

comment: Hilfe von C. Casalini, Prof. Albert Derolez
analysis:
Please find in attachment 3 photos of a handwritten added quire in our copy. The rest of the book has no handwritten comments or annotations.
"Louis Richeome societatis iesu in libro inscribit gallice, L'adieu de l'ame devote laissant le corps, inter caetera habet haec dialogismo xxiii de cursu temporis quem eo (?) inteso visor."
I looked at the manuscript notes in the printed book and wrote the pair down not without difficulty:

p. 215. Vide quam bene rapidissimum et insanissimum cursum vocet ex iis quae post hoc caput subiunxi manu scripta ex Lud(ovico) Richomine.

p. 220. Sis cum maiorem fidem adstruendam adiungi possunt quae scribuntur a Ludovico Richehomo per duas sequentes paginas manu scriptas  desumpta ex astrologorum calculationibus quibus omnia improbabilia, ne dicam monstrosa, continentur.

The handwritten pages to which they refer are thus drawn from Louis Richeome, apparently a well-known theologian. The complete transcription of said pages would be a very large work, and perhaps not even of interest to your correspondent.
provenance: Bibl. August. Gand 1672

comment: I believe the digital images come from copy 1.
analysis: Letter by Silvanus Phillips Thompson: This book is much rarer than the first folio Shakespeare, for while of that work no fewer than 156 copies are known to exist, there are only 68 copies of the first folio Gilbert known, and only two have been sold in the book auctions in the last twenty years. (see #785)

There is a list of errata in the back of the book, and it seems that a past reader fixed these mistakes by hand. It also seems that he made some of his own corrections and marginalia.
I am listing all instances below, divided by category.
Listed Errata: Pages 9, 61, 62, 72, 142, 211, 230
Unlisted Errata: Pages 14, 22, 47
Other Marginalia: Pages 38, 42, 67

The volume contains the Gilbert first, followed by three titles by Joseph Scaliger. The Gilbert has only a little annotation. For example, there is underlining on pages 7, 12, 13, and 17 (but I saw none on the intervening pages). There was a correction on page 11 to the Greek text, and a marginal note on page 19. The annotation continues in this vein, but sparsely.
I am attaching a pdf with images:
images 1-3 the extensive annotation in the front endleaves
images 4-5 the title page of the Gilbert and a closeup of the signature of the title page
images 6-8  the annotations to pages 11, 17, and 19, as examples of what is there.
There are more substantial annotations to the Scaliger titles. I will send a pdf of those three title pages and sample annotations in a separate email (my email system is sensitive to the size of my attachments)
Yes, the first three images on the pdf were of the  front endleaves of the volume, with their extensive annotations and the diagram. analysis:
Our only copy of the De magnete, magneticisque corporibus, et de magno magnete tellure..., London, 1600 (shelfmark S.A. 4747 V.) bears practically no handwritten annotations.
The exceptions are:
- An unidentified mark of reader or ownership in the title page (below the imprint), being “J. B. Leg. [?]”
- A few lines of text underlined (mainly in the initial pages);
- An handwritten correction of a word in page 47, line 19: “cè; ita Carabe, res oblate; xxxxx aut [handwritten] rapiens paleas, vt Scaliger ex Abo-“;
- Two handwritten annotations on the left margin of page 166, made in pencil, one aside the final paragraph of chapter VIII, the other aside the initial decorated capital of chapter IX. They are both so faded that I cannot read them.
In brief, the book has no critic or complementary hand notes, or, as you said, handwritten additions of substance.
I inform you that this copy of ours is in very good condition, and it is bound in parchment.

Library: University of Birmingham, Cadbury Research Library
analysis:
I have checked through every page within our copy of this book and taken some images for you (please see attached PDF document), sorry that these iPhone photographs are not higher quality.  If you find that any of the existing images aren’t quite clear enough for you, then just let me know and I can re-take any images for you when I am next on campus and able to access our book stores again.
Just to most directly answer your queries now, I can confirm there are no handwritten comments within our copy, despite this copy being interleaved with blank pages – presumably in anticipation of reader comment.
There are, however, present; some signatures on the title-page, as well as a number of hand emendations, and instances of hand underlining on certain pages.  All examples that have been identified have been photographed for you and included in the PDF document, in case these are of interest.
You will also see in the attached PDF an image of an article that was published in a newspaper, evidently from many years ago.  This press-cutting is laid loosely within our copy; I contacted our former Rare Book Librarian (he has recently retired) to check, and he does not believe that the press-cutting refers specifically to our copy of the book.  We suspect, then, that the inclusion of this by a previous owner may have been for contextual information around the history of Gilbert’s work, and perhaps particularly to note the references to emendations which are known to appear in multiple copies of the work.

A quick look at the copy here suggests that there are few very succinct pencil annotations but not a great number presumably made by Silvanus P. Thompson, former owner of the book, as part of his work on translating and commenting on the text at the very end of the nineteenth century and dawn of the twentieth century

analysis:
I have examined Gilbertus’ _De Magnete_ (Pembroke 10.9.9) for you and I have several subtle reader marks to report (all represented in the attached photos). The title page has two small annotations (top left in the gutter; right-hand margin between title and top of printer’s device). Indeed, as the catalogue notes there is a small correction on p. 11 of one of the Greek characters (7 lines from the bottom). Another handwritten correction in ink on p. 22 (quale to qualis). The catalogue notes that in many copies there are corrections additionally on pp. 47 and 63. To my eye, I did not see corrections on these two pages, but I am attaching images so you can be certain. I did find one additional reader mark on p. 218: a small cross in the fore-edge margin on line 13. There is also an historic library shelf mark on the fore edge.
The catalogue notes that the book was rebound in the 20th century (1985); unfortunately, if there were any original flyleaves with annotations, they are no longer extant, replaced by 3 modern (blank) flyleaves in the front and the back.

comment: It is the policy of the Dean and Chapter of the Cathedral that shelfmarks are not made public.
analysis: Thank you for your enquiry about our copy of William Gilbert, De Magnete (London: Peter Short, 1600). I have looked at the volume, and there is only one page on which there are manuscript annotations. On page 206, there is a diagram entitled: “Diagramma notuum in orbibus magneticis”. Two straight lines have been added to the diagram in leadpoint. One is very thick, and actually comprises several lines that don’t entirely overlap each other, which bisect the circles, going through points E, G, [unnamed point], and L, and continuing in a straight line through the four additional unnamed points to the other side of the circles. The other line is singular, and is perpendicular to the first one, bisecting the circles through eight unnamed points. I include two photos.
provenance: It is likely that this book was owned by Seth Ward (1617-1689), who was the Savilian professor of astronomy at Oxford, and one of the founder member of the Royal Society, before becoming Bishop of Salisbury in 1667. Upon his death in 1689, he bequeathed half of his collection of printed books to Salisbury Cathedral. Unfortunately, the book was rebound in the nineteenth-century, and any provenance information (Ward had his own unique system of press-marks) has been lost.

comment: checked again by Oscar Seip
analysis:
fol. *5r: Unterstreichung der Worte "vulgi captum" (vgl. Nachstellung anhand Weimarer Digitalsiat im Anhang)
S. 39: Korrektur "x" bei "vtrum que" genau wie in Weimar, Hannover mit anderer Korrektur an dieser Stelle
S. 47: Korrekture "Non rapiens" -> "Non" dreifach durchgestrichen und darüber "aut" eingetragen, sehr ähnlich der Korrektur in Weimar, keine in Hannover
S. 68: Korrektur "i" bei "ti fuerint", der Korrektur in Weimar sehr ähnlich, Hannover erneut optisch abweichend
S. 103: Korrektur "im" aus "ini- / mica", "n" und i" werden mit einem Bogen zu "m", der i-Punkt ist mit einem zweiten Strich getilgt ; hier keine Korrekturen in Weimar und Hannover (vgl. Anhang, Weimarer Digitalisat)
S. 167: Unterstreichung "(referente Hogone Grotio)"

Die Korrekturen sind stets in schwarzer Tinte ausgeführt, die Unterstreichungen auf fol. *5r und S. 167 sind in brauner Tinte ausgeführt.
provenance:
Unser Exmeplar 44 Phys. 2° findet sich auf Seite 1.000 im Bücherradkatalog und gehörte bereits im Oktober 1626 zur Büchersammlung von Herzog August (1579-1666). Dieser hat zwischen 1625 und 1627 seine bis dahin vorhandene Sammlung in einem Gesamtkatalog erfasst, der nach erster Beendigung 1627 als Zugangsbuch bis über Augusts Tod hinaus ergänzt und fortgeführt wurde. Ein genaueres Zugangsdatum ist nicht ermittelbar. Seit den 1640er Jahren befindet sich der Band vor Ort in Wolfenbüttel, nachdem Herzog August nach mehreren Jahren Wartezeit 1644 das Residenzschloss beziehen konnte.

In den ausgewerteten historischen Ausleihbüchern von 1664 bis 1806 konnte ich nur eine Entleihung des Bandes ermitteln.

Am 24. Februar 1676, also diese Woche Donnerstag vor genau 346 Jahren, wurde das Buch vom Küchenmeister und späteren Hochfürstlich Braunschweigisch-Lüneburgischen Haushofmeister Siegmund Georg Schöps (22.04.1632-17.04.1699) entliehen. Am gleichen Tag wurde ihm auch der folgende Band vorgelegt: https://opac.lbs-braunschweig.gbv.de/DB=2/XMLPRS=N/PPN?PPN=15103642X [Exemplar 8.2 Quod. (1)]

Es handelt sich um die ersten Entleihungen, die für Schöps belegbar sind. Bis 1696 hat er insgesamt zwölf Bände entliehen. Die Familie Schöps nutzte die herzogliche Bibliothek regelmäßig. Auch seine Ehefrau nimmt zwei Mal Einsicht in Handschriften ("gemalte Blumenbücher"). Der Sohn Rudolf Siegmund, Student in Helmstedt, entleiht innerhalb von zwei Jahren dreizehn Bände, das letzte nur wenige Wochen vor seinem Tod im Alter von 22 Jahren.

analysis: I’ve looked at our copy of the 1633 Tractatus. I has no marginalia or annotations, but lines on page 213 have been inked out, and then pages 214-225 were cut out. These pages include chapters IV, V, Vi, VII of Book Vi, treating of the circular motion of the earth and its magnetic nature. There are additional lines crossed out both in the index capitum and in the index rerum.
